PSEUDOMONAS - USA: (PENNSYLVANIA) NEONATAL INTENSIVE CARE UNIT, FATAL, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
**********************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 28 Oct 2019
Source: The Danville News [edited]
https://www.dailyitem.com/the_danville_news/news/geisinger-still-seeking-source-of-outbreak-blamed-in-infant-deaths/article_28239742-b89f-5775-a62f-ed80e85f4ffa.html


Geisinger and state [Pennsylvania] Health Department investigators still are searching for answers to a pseudomonas bacteria outbreak blamed in the death of 3 infants in Geisinger Medical Center's neonatal intensive care unit (NICU), Geisinger spokesman Joseph Stender said.
The medical center also still is giving expectant mothers expected to deliver before 32 weeks' gestation the option of going to another hospital, Stender said.

Eight newborns were sickened at the hospital by the outbreak. In addition to the 3 who died, 4 were treated and recovered and 1 was still undergoing treatment in recent weeks. Stender was trying to determine late [on Mon 28 Oct 2019] if that was still the case.

The parents of one of the infants who died in September [2019] filed a wrongful death lawsuit against Geisinger on [17 Oct 2019]. [The patient] was born prematurely at the hospital on [24 Sep 2019] and died in the NICU 6 days later. He was the last of 3 newborn infants to die at the hospital following the outbreak, according to attorney Matt Casey, of Philadelphia, who was hired by the infant's parents of Hazle Township, Luzerne County. [The patient] was the 8th newborn to be infected in the hospital's NICU since July [2019], the lawsuit contends. Among the allegations cited in the lawsuit is that Geisinger officials were aware of a trend of infections in early August [2019] but continued to accept premature infants into the NICU for more than a month and did not warn families of the potentially deadly outbreak.

Dr Rosemary Leeming, Geisinger's chief medical officer, said at a [7 Oct 2019] news conference that Geisinger would divert pregnant women likely to deliver at under 32 weeks' gestation to other facilities. Families of infants currently in the unit have the option of transferring their children to a facility in the Geisinger system or an outside facility, hospital officials said.

Three pregnant women expected to deliver before 32 weeks were diverted to Penn State Health Milton S Hershey Medical Center from Geisinger earlier this month [October 2019], Penn State Health spokesman Scott Gilbert confirmed.

[byline: Joe Sylvester]

